Czech Discovery: A substance that works on "endurant" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality, in some cases, takes the top on the fact that the combination does not deal as intensively with the current variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at present.
However, the life of the sick can be radically prolonged through a combination of medicines that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption results in a series of side effects.
Moreover, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs have no effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to confront the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalcarbores are an assembly of bore, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the resistance problem.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their links to virus proteins.
Metalcarbores have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages are formed by the bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms and linked by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a HIV protein that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, there would be no mature infectious particles in the virus.
If HIV is stopped, the spread of the virus in the patient's body will be stopped, explains researchers in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Republic Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
