Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than ten years, the attitude of managing large companies towards their employees has reminded them of the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is to make employees join "values" determined as they once were, to impose on consumers the products thought by the factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has given the procurement strategies to the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the company's intellectual functions, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment from employees that authoritarian management revenues are totally contrary.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would be to put the employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the customer.
The full usefulness of internal opinion investigations
Internal opinion surveys – such as Orange's questionnaire to its employees - will encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many diversions, to do priority... what it has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old Behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the "neurossciences" of the United States and widely disseminated, in their own sense, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of the executives' engagement, a recent survey of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts leaders in a position of mechanical governance, inadequate to the world of today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern businesses, requires the adoption of a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists in incorporating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means of achieving some of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
Currently, only motivational analysis studies adopt this concept of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a pre-determined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilisation factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and restore their management of human resources "to the place".
They thus create a land conducive to the concerted development of a robust and effective economic intelligence.
