Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As has happened with the ABS braking system and as will be done with ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory component on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen pedestrian protection, even if, by its way of action, it can also help to prevent many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing pressure on the brakes in case of emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always maintain pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all its strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
