New tools for the expertise of cars
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a loss are brought back to a garage, where an expert has to assess the damage suffered and the cost of repair.
Each disaster is different, and the calculation of the cost of the parts and the working time can be a long and complex work.
To calculate by hand the cost of a repair of between 20 000 and 30 000 euros, including the parts and the working hand can take two or three hours.
However, with the assistance of the latest computer tools, this would be a matter of minutes.
That is why almost 100 percent of experts use this type of system.
Service providers and solutions for disaster assessment and maintenance are dedicated to the collection of information provided by manufacturers, then to process and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other companies in competition in the field of evaluation tools and the development of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, so that over the past five years more versions, variants and motorizations have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car gets out on the market, these companies get to work.
This is very hard work, because each of the thousand pieces of the vehicle must be catalogued and the price entered.
In addition, a "intelligent" graphic image of each model on which you can click on the different parts of a tourism car is established.
If it is a model sold massively, the work can be ready within a week if the process progresses very quickly.
In the case of an unsold car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information about 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With respect to vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99 %.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audadex has eight centres distributed around the world (in Spain, France, Germany, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each is specialized in certain brands.
The national seat is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than one hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests annually 90 million to develop these databases.
Each month, 2.5 million data are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this huge flow of information enables these companies to provide different uses and offer various products.
